{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "04 ‚Äî Testing, Fakes & Closures",
  "description": "How to test Go code without a framework. This tour walks agent_test.go top-to-bottom: implementing an interface to fake a dependency, writing table-style tests, building closures for state capture, and verifying behaviour with the standard testing package.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent_test.go",
      "line": 13,
      "title": "4.1 ‚Äî The fake client struct",
      "description": "```go\ntype fakeClient struct {\n    turns []fakeTurn\n    calls int\n}\n\ntype fakeTurn struct {\n    text  string\n    tools []llm.ToolCall\n    err   error\n}\n```\n\nTests live in files named `*_test.go`. They're compiled only when running `go test` ‚Äî never included in the production binary.\n\n`fakeClient` is a local type that scripts a sequence of model responses. `turns` holds the scripted replies; `calls` tracks how many have been consumed.\n\nNotice both types are **unexported** (lowercase) ‚Äî they're only needed inside the test file. There's no reason to export them. Go rewards this: keeping things unexported by default reduces surface area and coupling."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent_test.go",
      "line": 24,
      "title": "4.2 ‚Äî Implementing an interface for testing",
      "description": "```go\nfunc (f *fakeClient) ChatStream(\n    ctx context.Context,\n    msgs []llm.Message,\n    tools []llm.ToolSpec,\n) (<-chan llm.Chunk, error) {\n    if f.calls >= len(f.turns) {\n        return nil, errors.New(\"fake: no more scripted turns\")\n    }\n    turn := f.turns[f.calls]\n    f.calls++\n    ch := make(chan llm.Chunk, 4)\n    go func() {\n        defer close(ch)\n        ...\n    }()\n    return ch, nil\n}\n```\n\n`fakeClient` satisfies `llm.Client` because it has `ChatStream` and `Embed` with the right signatures. No declaration needed ‚Äî Go checks at compile time.\n\nThe fake pops the next scripted turn (checking for exhaustion), increments `calls`, and returns a channel just like the real clients do. The goroutine + `defer close(ch)` pattern is identical to `internal/llm/openai.go` and `internal/kronk.Client` ‚Äî the caller can't tell the difference.\n\nThis is Go's standard testing pattern: **write a small type that satisfies the interface, script the behavior, inject it**. No mocking framework. The `Loop` in tests gets a `fakeClient` instead of the real `kronk.Client` or `OpenAIClient` ‚Äî it never knows. Tests run offline, at millisecond speed."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent_test.go",
      "line": 50,
      "title": "4.3 ‚Äî Closures and state capture",
      "description": "```go\nfunc collect(events *[]Event) func(Event) {\n    return func(e Event) { *events = append(*events, e) }\n}\n```\n\n`collect` is a **closure factory**: it takes a pointer to a slice and returns a function that captures (closes over) that pointer.\n\nEvery time the returned function is called ‚Äî every time `emit(e)` fires in the loop ‚Äî it appends to the slice behind the pointer. After `Run` returns, the caller inspects `events` to see exactly what happened.\n\nWhy `*[]Event` (pointer to slice) and not just `[]Event`? Because `append` may return a new backing array ‚Äî assigning back through the pointer is necessary to reflect the growth in the outer variable. `*events = append(*events, e)` dereferences and writes; without the `*` you'd be appending to a copy.\n\n**Try it:** change `*events = append(*events, e)` to `events = append(events, e)` (without the dereference). Run the tests ‚Äî they'll fail because the outer slice never grows. Then restore it."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent_test.go",
      "line": 54,
      "title": "4.4 ‚Äî A basic test: structure and assertions",
      "description": "```go\nfunc TestRunPlainAnswer(t *testing.T) {\n    loop := &Loop{Client: &fakeClient{turns: []fakeTurn{{text: \"hello\"}}}}\n\n    var events []Event\n    msgs, err := loop.Run(\n        context.Background(),\n        []llm.Message{{Role: \"user\", Content: \"hi\"}},\n        collect(&events),\n    )\n    if err != nil {\n        t.Fatalf(\"Run: %v\", err)\n    }\n    last := msgs[len(msgs)-1]\n    if last.Role != \"assistant\" || last.Content != \"hello\" {\n        t.Fatalf(\"unexpected final message: %+v\", last)\n    }\n```\n\nEvery `Test...` function receives `*testing.T`. No test framework, no `assert` library.\n\n- `t.Fatalf` ‚Äî mark test failed, stop this test immediately (like `return`)\n- `t.Errorf` ‚Äî mark test failed, continue running (useful for checking multiple things)\n- `t.Logf` ‚Äî print something, only visible on failure or with `-v`\n\n`context.Background()` is the root context ‚Äî no cancellation, no deadline. Tests use it when they don't need to simulate cancellation.\n\n`%+v` in format strings prints a struct with field names: `{Role:assistant Content:hello ToolCalls:[] ToolCallID:}` instead of just `{assistant hello [] }`. Very useful in test failure messages."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent_test.go",
      "line": 71,
      "title": "4.5 ‚Äî Testing a multi-step behaviour",
      "description": "```go\nfunc TestRunToolRound(t *testing.T) {\n    client := &fakeClient{turns: []fakeTurn{\n        {tools: []llm.ToolCall{{ID: \"c1\", Name: \"echo\", Args: `{\"s\":\"ping\"}`}}},\n        {text: \"the tool said ping\"},\n    }}\n    loop := &Loop{\n        Client: client,\n        Tools: []Tool{{\n            Spec: llm.ToolSpec{Name: \"echo\"},\n            Execute: func(ctx context.Context, args string) (string, error) {\n                return \"ping\", nil\n            },\n        }},\n    }\n```\n\nThis test scripts two turns:\n1. First model response: request the `echo` tool\n2. Second model response: plain text answer\n\nThe `Execute` function literal is defined inline ‚Äî exactly as production tools are in `internal/tools/os.go`. In Go you can define a function wherever you need one.\n\nAfter `Run`, the test verifies:\n- `tool_start` and `tool_result` events fired\n- The message history is `[assistant(tool_calls), tool(result), assistant(final)]` ‚Äî 3 messages\n- `msgs[1].ToolCallID == \"c1\"` ‚Äî the tool result is linked to the correct call\n\nThis is behavioural testing: we're not testing implementation details, we're testing the observable contract."
    },
    {
      "file": "internal/agent/agent_test.go",
      "line": 128,
      "title": "4.6 ‚Äî Testing failure modes",
      "description": "```go\nfunc TestRunStepLimit(t *testing.T) {\n    turns := make([]fakeTurn, 3)\n    for i := range turns {\n        turns[i] = fakeTurn{tools: []llm.ToolCall{{ID: \"x\", Name: \"echo\", Args: `{}`}}}\n    }\n    loop := &Loop{\n        Client:   &fakeClient{turns: turns},\n        MaxSteps: 2,\n        ...\n    }\n\n    _, err := loop.Run(context.Background(), nil, collect(&events))\n    if err == nil {\n        t.Fatal(\"expected step-limit error\")\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe model calls a tool forever. `MaxSteps: 2` caps it at 2 rounds. The test verifies that `Run` returns an error rather than looping indefinitely.\n\n`make([]fakeTurn, 3)` creates a slice of 3 zero-value `fakeTurn`s, then the `for i := range turns` loop fills each one. This is Go's table-driven test pattern at its smallest: a slice of inputs.\n\nFor larger tables you'd typically write:\n```go\ntests := []struct{ input string; want string }{\n    {\"a\", \"A\"},\n    {\"b\", \"B\"},\n}\nfor _, tt := range tests {\n    got := transform(tt.input)\n    if got != tt.want { t.Errorf(...) }\n}\n```\n\n**Run all tests now:**\n```\ngo test ./internal/agent/ -v\n```\nThe `-v` flag shows each test's name and duration."
    }
  ]
}
